# Detailed Report on the Reasons Behind the Increase in Oil Prices

The recent surge in oil prices has attracted significant attention from economists, policymakers, and market participants worldwide. Understanding the multifaceted reasons behind this increase requires an in-depth analysis of global supply and demand dynamics, geopolitical factors, production policies, and economic recovery trends. This report synthesizes information from a wide range of authoritative sources to provide a comprehensive and objective explanation of why oil prices are increasing.

---

## 1. Supply and Demand Fundamentals

### 1.1 Demand Recovery Post-Pandemic

One of the primary drivers of the recent rise in oil prices is the robust recovery in global demand following the COVID-19 pandemic. As vaccination campaigns progressed in major economies such as North America, Europe, and parts of Asia, lockdown restrictions eased, leading to increased mobility, industrial activity, and transportation needs. This resurgence in economic activity has translated into higher consumption of petroleum products, pushing demand closer to or even beyond pre-pandemic levels.

For instance, global oil demand, which was down by nearly 30 million barrels per day (bpd) in mid-April 2020, recovered to about 19 million bpd below pre-pandemic levels by mid-May 2020, signaling a strong rebound ([Capital.com, 2020](https://capital.com/oil-price-analysis-in-may-2020)). By late 2021 and into 2022, demand was expected to return fully to 2019 levels, contingent on the pace of GDP recovery and the duration of any remaining lockdowns ([McKinsey, 2021](https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/oil-and-gas/our-insights/global-oil-supply-and-demand-outlook-to-2040)).

### 1.2 Supply Constraints and OPEC+ Production Policies

On the supply side, the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) and its allies, collectively known as OPEC+, have played a decisive role in managing output to stabilize prices. Since 2016, OPEC+ has coordinated production cuts to counterbalance oversupply and support prices. At the beginning of 2020, OPEC members controlled about 71% of total world proved crude oil reserves and accounted for 36% of global production ([EIA, 2022](https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/oil-and-petroleum-products/prices-and-outlook.php)).

Despite the pandemic-induced demand shock, OPEC+ maintained output cuts totaling approximately 2.1 million bpd by March 2020, which helped prevent a further collapse in prices ([Capital.com, 2020](https://capital.com/oil-price-analysis-in-may-2020)). In 2021 and 2022, OPEC+ continued to carefully calibrate production to avoid excess supply, even suspending recovery programs temporarily if demand slowed, demonstrating their influence over market balance ([Weafer, 2021](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/oil-gas-prices-2022-scenarios-christopher-chris-weafer)).

### 1.3 U.S. Supply and Infrastructure Bottlenecks

While the United States remains a significant oil producer, especially with shale oil, its influence on global prices has diminished relative to OPEC+. Environmental activism and capital expenditure constraints have limited the expansion of U.S. oil production. Furthermore, infrastructural bottlenecks have constrained the ability of U.S. producers to offset OPEC+ cuts fully, contributing to tighter supply conditions ([Weafer, 2021](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/oil-gas-prices-2022-scenarios-christopher-chris-weafer); [CaixaBank Research, 2021](https://www.caixabankresearch.com/en/economics-markets/commodities/what-behind-rise-oil-prices)).

