## 2. Geopolitical and Market Sentiment Factors

### 2.1 Geopolitical Risks and Uncertainties

Geopolitical tensions, particularly in oil-rich regions such as the Middle East and Africa, have historically influenced oil prices by affecting supply expectations. Recent attacks on oil installations in Nigeria, Africa's largest oil producer, have raised concerns about export disruptions, contributing to upward price pressure ([Oil-Price.net, 2010](http://oil-price.net/en/articles/reasons-behind-oil-price-rise.php)).

Moreover, research indicates a positive and significant relationship between oil price volatility and geopolitical risk, with shocks in oil price volatility leading to immediate increases in geopolitical risk perceptions ([ScienceDirect, 2021](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1059056021002069)). This interplay tends to amplify market uncertainty and speculative premiums embedded in oil prices.

### 2.2 Market Expectations and Speculation

Oil prices also reflect market expectations about future supply and demand balances. Traders and investors factor in anticipated economic growth, potential supply disruptions, and policy changes. For example, the possibility of a return of Iranian oil exports to the market remains uncertain due to geopolitical and domestic political constraints in the U.S., limiting supply growth and supporting higher prices ([Weafer, 2021](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/oil-gas-prices-2022-scenarios-christopher-chris-weafer)).

Additionally, the current price levels embed expectations of sustained economic growth, particularly in Asia, where a relaxation of COVID-19 restrictions could further boost demand and push prices toward $100 per barrel for a period ([Conerly, 2021](https://www.forbes.com/sites/billconerly/2021/11/13/oil-forecast-2022-and-beyond/)).

---

## 3. Energy Market Interactions and Substitutions

### 3.1 Natural Gas and Coal Price Dynamics

The surge in natural gas and coal prices globally has had a knock-on effect on oil demand and prices. In Asia and Europe, shortages and high prices for natural gas have led to increased oil consumption as a substitute for power generation and industrial use. This substitution effect has added upward pressure on oil demand and prices ([Marca, 2021](https://www.marca.com/en/lifestyle/us-news/2021/10/24/617520d222601d10078b45ab.html); [PeakOil.com, 2022](https://peakoil.com/consumption/why-is-there-a-global-price-hike-in-the-oil-market)).

### 3.2 Refinery Utilization and Product Demand

Increased refinery utilization rates, particularly in the U.S., have also contributed to higher crude oil prices. For example, refinery utilization rose to 81.9% in late February 2010, the highest since October of that year, indicating strong demand for refined petroleum products ([Oil-Price.net, 2010](http://oil-price.net/en/articles/reasons-behind-oil-price-rise.php)). The transportation sector's near-total dependence on petroleum fuels ensures that rising gasoline and diesel demand directly supports crude oil prices.

---

## 4. Historical and Structural Factors

### 4.1 Long-Term Price Equilibrium and Cost Structures

Long-term forecasts suggest that oil prices will remain elevated compared to the pandemic lows but may not return to the pre-fracking era highs of $100 per barrel consistently. Structural changes, such as a flattening cost curve and lower demand growth due to energy transition efforts, have moderated long-term price expectations to a range of $50 to $60 per barrel under OPEC-controlled scenarios ([McKinsey, 2021](https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/oil-and-gas/our-insights/global-oil-supply-and-demand-outlook-to-2040)).

### 4.2 Demand Shocks vs. Supply Shocks

Empirical studies emphasize that demand shocks have played a more significant role than supply shocks in recent oil price fluctuations. For example, the sharp oil price decline from 2014 to 2016 was primarily driven by weakening demand rather than increased U.S. shale supply ([ScienceDirect, 2018](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0140988318302020)). This underscores the importance of global economic activity and consumer behavior in shaping oil prices.

